{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1781555112,"nonce":"LpDbolXU4yO1mUJSsf6aquK/DIE=","message":"Preferred direction: make the diff *semantically* predicate-aware rather than matching pg_get_expr text byte-for-byte.\n\nInstead of normalizing the desired predicate/CHECK string to the backend's exact deparse form (the round-trip-to-pg approach), parse both the desired and the introspected expression into a small shared expression AST and compare those, ignoring surface differences (identifier quoting, redundant parens, literal type casts, boolean case). This makes the diff robust by construction across backends and pg versions, and removes the need to reproduce pg's deparse at all.\n\nCost: a small SQL boolean-expression parser (columns, literals, IS [NOT] NULL, comparison ops, AND/OR/NOT, parens, casts) plus a normalized AST with structural equality; the diff for index predicates / CHECK expressions switches from string equality to AST equality. Bigger than the offline transform but the cleaner long-term shape. The pg round-trip is the lower-risk fallback if we do not want a parser.","files":null}]}